subSubSection.paragraph:
Synelmis gorgonensis
(
Monro, 1933
)

n. comb.
(
Figs 1D, E
; 
7
)

Eyes of different size, in straight transverse line, each with two eyes; external eyes larger than internal ones and left smaller one is double (each is abouth half the size of the complete one on the right side) in 
holotype
(
Fig. 7A
). The small juvenile from 
Chile
has lateral eyes fused into a single reniform eye, slightly behind the lateral antennae. Anterior (
Fig. 7B
), median (
Fig. 7C
), and posterior parapodia (
Fig. 7D
) with dorsal and ventral cirri very swollen, much wider than setal lobe; dorsal cirrus has its distal tip well defined and sometimes it appears jointed (even in the juvenile they are wider than the setal lobe). Most cirri have pigmented glands, appear darker than the rest of the body. Pigmented, small glandular areas behind the dorsal cirri in setigers 18-60. Interramal glands present in several anterior and posterior setigers; glands internal, can be seen above the setal lobe in lateral observation of the body.
